1 Introduction

1.1 General approach to creating graphics

LAPOP/CGD has created functions in Stata and R to make the process of creating data visualization simple and standardized. It involves two basic steps: pre-processing using lpr_ commands (in Stata or R) then designing the graphic using the lapop_ commands (in R). Four preparatory steps are necessary before beginning analysis:

  1. Create project folder (on your machine or on Box), where scripts and graphics will be saved
  2. [if using Stata] Create .do file (and change directory to project folder with command cd)
  3. Create R script (and set working directory to project folder with command setwd()).
  4. Load lapop package in R session with library(lapop) and load fonts with lapop_fonts()

If you choose to use Stata, the .do file is where you will process the data, including dataset reshaping, recodes, relabelling, and variable creation. The lpr Stata commands analyze the data while simultaneously formatting the results and packaging them into a specific output format (a .csv file). You will then take the .csv file, saved in the project folder, and read it into R as a data frame. The lapop_ R graphing functions take these data frames as input to produce the figures.

Instead, if you prefer to use R only, you can use the equivalent lpr_ commands with the lapop package to pre-process the data. You will simply save the tables as R objects, instead of .csvs.

Commands beginning with lpr_ take AmericasBarometer data, summarize it according to your inputs, and package the results into a neatly organized table. The functions beginning with lapop_ take those tables and graph them according to CGD style guidelines. Use the lpr_ commands to change the data, and the lapop_ functions to adjust the look of the graphics.

The help files for the Stata ados and the R package provide more detailed information about each command. Please consult these if you have any questions or would like to learn more about a specific graphing function. Use help lapop or help commandName in Stata and ?lapop or ?functionName to access the help files.

1.2 Installing package and ados

Upon first use, it is necessary to install the lapop R package and the ado files in order to use the commands in this guide.

1.2.1 Stata

Steps for First Install:

  1. Remove all previous lpr_ files from your personal ado directory (if necessary)
  2. In Stata: net install lpr, from("https://gitfront.io/r/cjwilson/AwTsqMVomrDu/lpr-ados/raw")
  3. In Stata: lpr_update (did you find the Easter egg?)

In the future, to check for updates:

  1. Stata: ado update lpr, update
  2. If you see something abou t packages to be updatedinstalling updatescleaning up, done then give the command: lpr_update
  3. If you see something like (no packages require updating), then you are up-to-date and dont need to rerun lpr_update (although there is no harm)
  4. To see changes, type or click help lpr

1.2.2 R

For first install, or to update package:

# install.packages("devtools")
# # install devtools package if you have not already done so

devtools::install_github("lapop-central/lapop")

You should also make one change in the settings of RStudio to avoid an issue where text within a graph overlaps.

  1. Navigate to Tools in the top toolbar
  2. Select Global Options
  3. In the General page (default), click the Graphics tab in the top-center
  4. Change Backend from (Default) to AGG
  5. Leave Antialiasing as-is
  6. Click Apply then OK.

In each R session:

library(lapop)
# lapop_fonts()

## or, when producing graphics for designed reports, use
lapop_fonts_design()

1.3 Reading in data

1.3.1 Stata

In Stata, read in the data with the use command. You can read in multiple datasets and switch between them by using frames, as shown in this example.

frame create ts
frame change ts
use "C:\Users\plutowl\Box\LAPOP Shared\2_Projects\2023 AB\JAM\Data Processing\JAM merge 2006-2023 LAPOP AmericasBarometer (v1.0s).dta", clear
lab lang en

frame create cc
frame change cc
use "C:\Users\plutowl\Box\LAPOP Shared\2_Projects\2023 AB\Core_Regional\Data Processing\YM\Merge 2023 LAPOP AmericasBarometer (v1.0s).dta", clear
lab lang en

1.3.2 R

Load the datasets you need with the lpr_data function, using the file path/name as the only argument. This will apply the appropriate weights and other dataset features so that the other lpr_ commands work as intended.

Note: The lpr commands currently do not support switching between languages. If you want the data to be displayed in a language other than the default (Spanish for merges and Spanish-speaking countries, English for English- and other non-Spanish-speaking countries), you will need to first open the dataset in Stata, change the language (e.g., lab lang en), and resave it.

jm23 <- lpr_data("C:/Users/plutowl/Box/LAPOP Shared/2_Projects/2023 AB/JAM/Data Processing/JAM merge 2006-2023 LAPOP AmericasBarometer (v1.0s).dta")

ym23 <- lpr_data("C:/Users/plutowl/Box/LAPOP Shared/2_Projects/2023 AB/Core_Regional/Data Processing/YM/Merge 2023 LAPOP AmericasBarometer (v1.0s).dta")

# #exclude US and Canada
# ym23 <- ym23 %>%
#   filter(!(pais %in% c(40, 41)))

1.4 Style Guidelines

  • File names: .csv and graphics files should have the same name. Their names should be in the following standard format: CountryYear/ts_DVcode(s)_IVcode(s)_graphtype.filetype.

    • Examples:
      • mex21_countfair1_hist.csv
      • hndts_b4_ts.svg
      • ab23_vic1ext_pais_cc.png
    • There will be some cases that do not easily fit this standard. Use your best judgment to follow the general standard while incorporating all relevant information. Examples:
      • hti20_ing4_demog_mover (breakdown of ing4 over demographic variables)
      • nic22_q14_full_coef (regression coefficients predicting q14 in full model)
      • jam21_genor_stack (stacked bar graph of genor series)

  • Subtitles should describe the actual meaning of the data shown. The (new) LAPOP standard is to start the subtitle with who. For example, % who trust elections instead of % trust elections, % trust in elections, or % trusting elections. This Excel sheet details how specific variables should be referenced.

  • Source information should be in the following format: LAPOP Lab, AmericasBarometer [Off-Cycle] [Country/LAC region] [year or wave]. Examples of correct formatting:

    • LAPOP Lab, AmericasBarometer Colombia 2021
    • LAPOP Lab, AmericasBarometer LAC Region 2016/17-2021
    • LAPOP Lab, AmericasBarometer Colombia 2016-2021
    • LAPOP Lab, AmericasBarometer Off-Cycle Guatemala 2012-2022

  • For toplines, do not add titles to graphs; the titles should be added as headers to the Powerpoint slides.

  • The default range for the y-axes for all graphs is 0-100. This is the standard for LAPOP graphs, as most of our reporting relies on percentages. Change these defaults only if the scale necessitates it (e.g., if using the original variable scale).

  • For time-series graphs, the LAPOP standard is to use the variable year when using data from one country and wave for regional or multi-country data.

1.5 Note for auditors

All of the lpr Stata commands offer a special option when auditing, audit("C:\here is a\file.csv"). This is how it works:

  1. Player 1 create a graph using the command lpr_cc aoj11 pais, file("c:\temp\P1.csv" ) num(1 2) denom(3 4 .a .b)
  2. Player 2 is auditing the graph and received P1.csv. P2 reads the text and thinks the command is lpr_cc aoj11 pais, num(1 2) audit("c:\myplace\P1.csv"). The audit option compares the current command output with the contents of P1. Because P2 did not include denom(3 4 .a .b), the results are different and P2 gets a bunch of messages to that effect in Stata.
  3. 2 says Ah, I bet P1 included the missing values! and runs the command lpr_cc aoj11 pais, audit("c:\temp\P1.csv" ) num(1 2) denom(3 4 .a .b). Stata tells P2 that the results match. P2 tells P1 to be clearer in the text about the inclusion of missing values.

Note that P2 could have added the filesave option if they wanted a copy of the .csv produced by their command, but it isnt necessary.

1.6 Rescaling variables

The lpr_resc commands (available in both Stata and R) allow you to rescale and reverse the coding of different variables.

For example, the following code will reverse the labels of the variable and rescale it to go from 0 to 1:

jm23$variables$aoj11r <- lpr_resc(jm23$variables$aoj11, reverse = TRUE, map = TRUE)
##                  
##                      0 0.333333333333333 0.666666666666667    1
##   Very safe          0                 0                 0 4674
##   Somewhat safe      0                 0              5902    0
##   Somewhat unsafe    0              1794                 0    0
##   Very unsafe     1093                 0                 0    0

2 Graph types

2.1 Cross-country bar plot ( lpr_cc / lapop_cc)

Note: Despite the name, this bar graph can be used to show the summary (e.g., the average) of a variable over any secondary variable, not just country (pais). It can also be useful to show a summary for several interrelated variables, such as the percentage of respondents who chose each category in a check all that apply question (the hist commands would not be appropriate as it is intended to show the distribution of a single variable).

2.1.1 Stata

Syntax:

lpr_cc yvar xvar [if] [in] [weight][, options]

Example:

lpr_cc vic1ext pais, num(1) filesave("AB23_vic1ext_cc.csv")

2.1.2 R

Syntax (to process data):

lpr_cc(data,
       outcome,
       xvar = "pais_lab",
       rec = c(1, 1),
       ci_level = 0.95,
       mean = FALSE,
       filesave = "",
       cfmt = "",
       sort = "y",
       order = "hi-lo",
       ttest = FALSE,
       keep_nr = FALSE)

Syntax (to create graphic):

lapop_cc(data,                      
         ymin = 0,
         ymax = 100,
         lang = "en",
         highlight = "",
         main_title = "",
         source_info = "",
         subtitle = "",
         sort = "",
         color_scheme = "#784885",
         label_size = 5)

Example:

## If using Stata...
# vic1ext_cc <- read.csv("AB23_vic1ext_cc.csv")

vic1ext_cc <- lpr_cc(ym23,
                    outcome = "vic1ext",
                    xvar = "pais_lab",
                    rec = c(1, 1))

vic1ext_cc_fig <- lapop_cc(vic1ext_cc,
                         source_info = ", AmericasBarometer 2023",
                         subtitle = "% who were crime victims",
                         highlight = "JM",
                         main_title = "Jamaica reports nearly the lowest level of crime victimization in the region")

To save:

lapop_save(vic1ext_cc_fig, "AB23_vic1ext_cc.svg", width_px = 950)

To display:

vic1ext_cc_fig

2.2 Grouped bar plot (multi-cross-country bar plot) ( lpr_ccm / lapop_ccm)

2.2.1 Stata

Syntax:

lpr_ccm yvar1 yvar2 xvar [if] [in] [weight][, options]

Example:

lpr_ccm exc2 exc6 pais, num(1) num2(1) filesave("AB23_exc_ccm.csv", replace) xlabs ysort(-)

2.2.2 R

Syntax (to process data):

lpr_ccm(data,
        outcome_vars,
        xvar = "pais_lab",
        rec1 = c(1, 1),
        rec2 = c(1, 1),
        rec3 = c(1, 1),
        ci_level = 0.95,
        mean = FALSE,
        filesave = "",
        cfmt = "",
        sort = "y",
        order = "hi-lo",
        ttest = FALSE,
        keep_nr = FALSE)

Syntax (to create graphic):

lapop_ccm(data,
          ymin = 0,
          ymax = 100,
          lang = "en",
          main_title = "",
          source_info = "",
          subtitle = "",
          sort = "",
          y_label = "",
          x_label = "",
          highlight = "",
          color_scheme = c("#784885", "#008381", "#C74E49"),
          label_size = 4,
          text_position = 0.7)

Example:

## if using Stata...
# exc_ccm <- read.csv("AB23_exc_ccm.csv")

exc_ccm <- lpr_ccm(ym23, 
                   outcome_vars = c("exc2", "exc6"),
                   rec1 = c(1, 1),
                   rec2 = c(1, 1))

exc_ccm$var <- ifelse(exc_ccm$var == "exc2", "Police", "Government employee")
exc_ccm_fig <- lapop_ccm(exc_ccm,
                         ymax = 60,
                         main_title = "Less than one in ten Jamaicans were asked to pay a bribe in the past year",
                         subtitle = "% who were asked to pay bribe by...",
                         highlight = "JM",
                         source_info = ", AmericasBarometer 2023")

To save:

lapop_save(exc_ccm_fig, "exc_ccm_fig.svg")

To display:

exc_ccm_fig

2.3 Side-by-side (combined) cross-country bar plot (lapop_cccomb)

This command works differently than the others. This function takes two lapop_cc in R and combines them into a side-by-side graphic. Its intended purpose is to display one independent variable with two dependent variables (in contrast to lapop_mover, which shows one dependent variable across two or more independent variables).

This is an R function only; there is no corresponding command in Stata.

Syntax:

lapop_cccomb <- function(cc1, cc2,
                         subtitle1 = "",
                         subtitle2 = "",
                         main_title = "",
                         source_info = "",
                         lang = "en",
                         color_scheme = "#784885",
                         file_name = "",
                         width_px = 895,
                         height_px = 600
)

Example:

ing4_aoj12_cc <- lpr_cc(jm23[jm23$variables$year == 2023],
                    outcome = "ing4",
                    xvar = "aoj12",
                    rec = c(5, 7),
                    sort = "xv",
                    order = "hi-lo")
ing4_aoj12_cc_fig <- lapop_cc(ing4_aoj12_cc)

pn4_aoj12_cc <- lpr_cc(jm23[jm23$variables$year == 2023],
                    outcome = "pn4",
                    xvar = "aoj12",
                    rec = c(1, 2),
                    sort = "xv",
                    order = "hi-lo")

pn4_aoj12_cc_fig <- lapop_cc(pn4_aoj12_cc)

lapop_cccomb(cc1 = ing4_aoj12_cc_fig, 
            cc2 = pn4_aoj12_cc_fig,
            subtitle1 = "% who support democracy",
            subtitle2 = "% who are satisfied with democracy",
            main_title = "Those who trust the judiciary have more positive views of democracy",
            source_info = ", AmericasBarometer Jamaica 2023", 
            file_name = "vic1ext_cccomb.svg")

Note here that, in contrast to the other lapop_ functions, lapop_cccomb requires you to save figures by specifying the file name within the function itself, rather than using lapop_save.

2.4 Coefficient plot (lpr_coef / lapop_coef)

2.4.1 Stata

Syntax:

lpr_coef regress/logit/probit depvar indepvars [if] [in] [weight], options

Example:

lpr_coef regress ing4 q1tc_r wealth edre vic1ext, contrast est(coef) filesave("jam23_ing4_coef.csv", replace)

2.4.2 R

Syntax (to process data):

lpr_coef(
  outcome = NULL,
    xvar = NULL,
    model = "gaussian",
    lprdata = NULL,
    estimate = c("coef"),
    vlabs = NULL,
    omit = NULL,
    filesave = NULL,
    replace = FALSE,
    level = 0.95
)

Syntax (to produce graphic):

lapop_coef(data, 
           lang = "en",
           main_title = "",
           subtitle = "",
           source_info = "",
           ymin = NULL,
           ymax = NULL,
           pred_prob = FALSE,
           color_scheme = "#784885",
           subtitle_h_just = 0)

Example:

## if using Stata
# ing4_coef <- read.csv("jam23_ing4_coef.csv")

ing4_coef <- lpr_coef(outcome="ing4", 
                    xvar="q1tc_r+wealth+edre+vic1ext", 
                    data=jm23[jm23$variables$year == 2023], 
                    est="coef", 
                    omit = "(Intercept)")
## CSV output file not created.
ing4_coef$varlabel <- c("Woman", "Wealth", "Education", "Crime Victim")

ing4_coef_fig <- lapop_coef(ing4_coef, 
           ymin = -0.5, 
           ymax = 0.5,
           main_title = "Wealthier Jamaicans are more likely to support democracy",
           source_info = ", AmericasBarometer Jamaica 2023")

To save:

lapop_save(ing4_coef_fig, "ing4_coef_fig.svg", width_px = 752, height_px = 720)

To display:

ing4_coef_fig

2.5 Dummbell plot (lpr_dumb / lapop_dumb)

2.5.1 Stata

Syntax:

lpr_dumb varname [if] [in] [weight], options

Example:

lpr_dumb jc15a, num(1) range(2016 2018) filesave("abgm_jc15a_2016_2018_dumb.csv")

2.5.2 R

Syntax (to process data):

lpr_dumb(data,
         outcome,
         xvar = "pais",
         over,
         rec = c(1, 1),
         ci_level = 0.95,
         mean = FALSE,
         filesave = "",
         cfmt = "",
         sort = "prop2",
         order = "hi-lo",
         ttest = FALSE,
         keep_nr = FALSE)

Syntax (to produce graphic):

lapop_dumb(data,
           ymin = 0,
           ymax = 100,
           lang = "en",
           main_title = "",
           source_info = "",
           subtitle = "",
           sort = "wave2",
           order = "hi-lo",
           color_scheme = c("#008381", "#A43D6A"),
           subtitle_h_just = 40,
           subtitle_v_just = -18,
           text_nudge = 6,
           drop_singles = FALSE)

Example:

# # if using Stata, read in csv
abgm_jc15a_2016_2018_dumb <- read.csv("abgm_jc15a_2016_2018_dumb.csv")

# abgm_jc15a_2016_2018_dumb <- lpr_dumb(abgm,
#                                       outcome = "jc15a",
#                                       xvar = "pais",
#                                       over = c(2016, 2018),
#                                       sort = "prop2")

abgm_jc15a_2016_2018_dumb_fig <- lapop_dumb(abgm_jc15a_2016_2018_dumb, 
                                 main_title = "Tolerance for executive coups expanded in most countries in 2018/19",
                                 source_info = ", AmericasBarometer 2016-2019")

To save:

lapop_save(abgm_jc15a_2016_2018_dumb_fig, "abgm_jc15a_2016_2018_dumb.svg", height = 750, width_px = 750)

To display:

abgm_jc15a_2016_2018_dumb_fig

2.6 Histogram / bar plot (lpr_hist / lapop_hist)

2.6.1 Stata

Syntax:

lpr_hist xvar [if] [in] [weight], options

Example:

lpr_hist exc7pan if year == 2023, filesave("JAM23ts_exc7pan_hist.csv", replace)

2.6.2 R

Syntax (to process data):

lpr_hist(data,
         outcome,
         filesave = "",
         cfmt = "",
         sort = "xv",
         order = "lo-hi",
         keep_nr = FALSE)

Syntax (to produce graphic):

lapop_hist(data, 
           ymin = 0,
           ymax = 100,
           lang = "en",
           main_title = "",
           subtitle = "",
           source_info = "",
           order = FALSE,
           color_scheme = "#008381")

Example:

## if using Stata...
# exc7pan_hist <- read.csv("JAM23ts_exc7pan_hist.csv")

exc7pan_hist <- lpr_hist(jm23,
                         outcome = "exc7pan",
                         order = "hi-lo")


exc7pan_hist_fig <- lapop_hist(exc7pan_hist,
                               main_title = "Jamaicans think that COVID-related corruption was common",
                               source_info = ", AmericasBarometer Jamaica 2023",
                               subtitle = ""
                               
)

To save:

lapop_save(exc7pan_hist_fig, "JAM23ts100_exc7pan_hist.svg")

To display:

exc7pan_hist_fig

2.7 Multi-line time-series plot (lpr_mline / lapop_mline)

This type of plot shows a time-series graph with multiple lines: either multiple lines for multiple outcome variables, or one outcome variable broken down by a secondary variable.

2.7.1 Stata

Syntax:

lpr_mline yvar pais [if] [in] [weight], options

Example:

lpr_mline q14 vic1ext, over(year) num(1) filesave("jamts_q14_vic1ext_mline.csv", replace)

2.7.2 R

Syntax (to process data):

lpr_mline(data,
                   outcome,
                   rec = c(1, 1),
                   rec2 = c(1, 1),
                   rec3 = c(1, 1),
                   rec4 = c(1, 1),
                   xvar,
                   use_wave = FALSE,
                   ci_level = 0.95,
                   mean = FALSE,
                   filesave = "",
                   cfmt = "",
                   ttest = FALSE,
                   keep_nr = FALSE)

Syntax (to produce graphic):

lapop_mline(data,
            ymin = 0,
            ymax = 100,
            main_title = "",
            source_info = "",
            subtitle = "",
            lang = "en",
            legend_h_just = 40,
            legend_v_just = -20,
            subtitle_h_just = 0,
            color_scheme = c("#784885", "#008381", "#c74e49", "#2d708e", "#a43d6a", "#202020"),
            percentages = TRUE,
            all_labels = FALSE,
            ci = FALSE,
            legendnrow = 1)

Example:

# # if using Stata, load csv into R
# q14_vic1ext_mline <- read.csv("jam23ts_q14_vic1ext_mline.csv")

#two approaches: 1. show one outcome variable broken down by another
q14_vic1ext_mline <- lpr_mline(jm23,
                               outcome = "q14",
                               xvar = "vic1ext")

q14_vic1ext_mline$varlabel <- ifelse(q14_vic1ext_mline$varlabel == "Yes", "Crime victims", "Non-victims")

q14_vic1ext_mline_fig <- lapop_mline(q14_vic1ext_mline,
                                     main_title = "Crime victims are more likely to emigrate than non-victims",
                                     subtitle = "% who intend to emigrate",
                                     source_info = ", AmericasBarometer Jamaica 2010-2023")

#2. multiple outcome variables across time
coups_mline <- lpr_mline(jm23,
                       outcome = c("jc10", "jc13"),
                       rec = 1,
                       rec2 = 1,
                       use_wave = FALSE)

coups_mline$varlabel <- ifelse(coups_mline$varlabel == "Coup is justified when there is a lot of corruption",
                               "Corruption", "Crime")

coups_mline_fig <- lapop_mline(coups_mline, 
                               subtitle = "% who say coup is justified when there is a lot of...",
                               all_labels = TRUE)

To save:

lapop_save(q14_vic1ext_mline_fig, "jam23ts_q14_vic1ext_mline.svg")

To display:

q14_vic1ext_mline_fig

coups_mline_fig

2.8 Multiple-over breakdown plot (lpr_mover / lapop_mover)

2.8.1 Stata

Syntax:

lpr_mover varlist [if] [in] [weight], options

Example:

lpr_mover b2 male edad wealth, num(5 6 7) filesave("jam23ts_b2_mover.csv", replace)

2.8.2 R

Syntax (to process data):

lpr_mover(data,
          outcome,
          grouping_vars,
          rec = c(1, 1),
          ci_level = 0.95,
          mean = FALSE,
          filesave = "",
          cfmt = "",
          ttest = FALSE,
          keep_nr = FALSE
)

Syntax (to produce graphic):

lapop_mover(
  data,
  lang = "en",
  main_title = "",
  subtitle = "",
  source_info = "",
  rev_values = FALSE,
  rev_variables = FALSE,
  subtitle_h_just = 0,
  ymin = 0,
  ymax = 100,
  x_lab_angle = 90,
  color_scheme = c("#784885", "#00adaa", "#c74e49", "#2d708e", "#a43d6a")
)

Example:

## if using Stata, read in csv
# b2_mover <- read.csv("jam23_b2_mover.csv")

b2_mover <- lpr_mover(jm23[jm23$variables$year == 2023],
                      outcome = "b2",
                      grouping_vars = c("q1tc_r", "edad", "wealth"),
                      rec = c(5, 7))
b2_mover$vallabel[1] <- "Men"
b2_mover$vallabel[2] <- "Women"

b2_mover_fig <- lapop_mover(b2_mover,
                                 source_info = ", AmericasBarometer Jamaica 2023",
                                 subtitle = "% who respect political institutions",
                                 main_title = "Older Jamaicans and the least wealthy are more likely to respect the political\ninstitutions of Jamaica",
                                 x_lab_angle = 0)

To save:

lapop_save(b2_mover_fig, "jam23_b2_mover.svg", width_px = 900)

To display:

b2_mover_fig

2.9 Stacked bar plot (lpr_stack / lapop_stack)

This graph can show the distributions of several outcome variables, or the distribution of one outcome variable broken down by a secondary variable.

2.9.1 Stata

Syntax:

lpr_stack varlist [if] [in] [weight], options

Example:

lpr_stack countfair1 countfair3, filesave("JAM23ts100_stack.csv", replace)

2.9.2 R

Syntax (to process data):

lpr_stack(data,
          outcome,
          by = NULL,
          sort = "xv",
          order = "lo-hi",
          filesave = "",
          keep_nr = FALSE)

Syntax (to produce graphic):

lapop_stack(data,
            lang = "en",
            main_title = "",
            subtitle = "",
            source_info = "",
            rev_values = FALSE,
            rev_variables = FALSE,
            hide_small_values = TRUE,
            order_bars = FALSE,
            subtitle_h_just = 0,
            fixed_aspect_ratio = TRUE,
            legendnrow = 1,
            color_scheme = c("#2D708E", "#008381", "#C74E49", "#784885", "#a43d6a","#202020"))

Example:

## if using Stata, read in csv
# countfair_stack <- read.csv("JAM23ts100_stack.csv")

countfair_stack <- lpr_stack(jm23[jm23$variables$year == 2023],
                             outcome = c("countfair1", "countfair3"))
countfair_stack$varlabel <- ifelse(countfair_stack$varlabel == "Perception of a secret ballot", "Polticians can find\nout who each person\nvoted for", "Votes are counted\ncorrectly and fairly")


countfair_stack_fig <- lapop_stack(countfair_stack,
                                   main_title = "Most Jamaicans discredit fair elections and the secret ballot",
                                   source_info = ", AmericasBarometer Jamaica 2023",
                                   subtitle = "",
                                   rev_values = TRUE,
                                   subtitle_h_just = -30
)

To save:

lapop_save(countfair_stack_fig, "JAM23ts100_countfair_stack.svg", width_px = 800)

To display:

countfair_stack_fig

2.10 Time-series plot (lpr_ts / lapop_ts)

2.10.1 Stata

Syntax:

lpr_ts yvar xvar [if] [in] [weight], options

Example:

lpr_ts aoj12 year, num(1 2) filesave("JAM23ts100_aoj12_ts.csv", replace)

2.10.2 R

Syntax (to process data):

lpr_ts(data,
       outcome,
       rec = c(1, 1),
       use_wave = FALSE,
       ci_level = 0.95,
       mean = FALSE,
       filesave = "",
       cfmt = "",
       ttest = FALSE,
       keep_nr = FALSE)

Syntax (to produce graphic):

lapop_ts(data, 
         ymin = 0,
         ymax = 100,
         main_title = "",
         source_info = "",
         subtitle = "",
         lang = "en",
         color_scheme = "#A43D6A",
         percentages = TRUE)

Example:

## if using Stata, read in csv
# aoj12_ts <- read.csv("JAM23ts100_aoj12_ts.csv")

aoj12_ts <- lpr_ts(jm23,
                   outcome = "aoj12",
                   rec = c(1, 2))


aoj12_ts_fig <- lapop_ts(aoj12_ts,
                         main_title = "A record low number of people think the judiciary would punish a criminal",
                         source_info = ", AmericasBarometer Jamaica 2006-2023",
                         subtitle = "% who trust that judiciary will punish the guilty"
)

To save:

lapop_save(aoj12_ts_fig, "JAM23ts100_aoj12_ts.svg", width_px = 850)

To display:

aoj12_ts_fig

3 FAQ/Common Issues

3.1 Is there an example .do file and R script that I can use to build my own files?

Yes. It is available on Box, or you can email Luke (luke.plutowski@vanderbilt.edu).

3.2 Why are numbers/symbols dissappearing from my R graphs?

This is usually fixed just by restarting R.

3.3 How do I get characters with Spanish accents to show up?

When reading in the csv, use latin1 encoding: df <- read.csv("ex.csv", encoding = "latin1")

3.4 Cannot install devtools package

Try updating to the latest version of R. If you still have trouble, try adding the argument dependencies = TRUE to the install.packages("devtools") command.

3.5 I am getting an error when I try to install the lapop R package

Try adding the option force = TRUE.

3.6 I receive warning messages when loading lapop_fonts()

You may get a message like this:

1: In file.rename(tmp, destfile):

cannot rename file

C:\Users\...' to 'C:\Users\...', reason 'Access is denied'

These messages can be ignored. This happens when temporary files are saved over one another when pulling fonts from Google; the fonts should still load.

3.7 Why does a new window pop up when saving graphs (R Graphics: Device 2 (inactive))?

Long story short: This is normal and you can just close the new window.

This is a graphics device, where the different elements of the plot are constructed and displayed. The lapop_save() command opens a new graphics device, saves the plot, and then immediately closes it (which is why no graph is displayed). Normally, graphics are shown within RStudio in the Viewer pane (lower-right). However, the graphics do not properly preview in this pane when attempting to do so within another function like lapop_save(). Therefore, it is necessary to open a new graphics device temporarily in order to save the graph and ensure that the image file resembles what is displayed in the Viewer pane.
## Text is distorted/overlapping

Sometimes, label text in the saved graphs can become jumbled. See example below:

If you have not already done so, set the Graphics Backend to AGG, as outlined in the installation section above:

  1. Navigate to Tools in the top toolbar
  2. Select Global Options
  3. In the General page (default), click the Graphics tab in the top-center
  4. Change Backend from (Default) to AGG
  5. Leave Antialiasing as-is
  6. Click Apply then OK.

If you have already done this, try closing RStudio and opening it again.

3.8 Can I/how do I do x with the graphs?

Check the help files in Stata (help commandName and R (?functionName). If you cannot find the answer there, email Carole (c.j.wilson@vanderbilt.edu) for Stata issues or Luke (luke.plutowski@vanderbilt.edu) for R issues.
